  "prompt": "What is the difference between high fidelity and actual design?",
  "response": "The terms \"high fidelity\" and \"actual design\" are often used in the context of design and prototyping, particularly in digital and user experience design.\n\n**High Fidelity Design:**\nHigh fidelity design refers to detailed, realistic, and fully functional prototypes. These designs are created to closely resemble the final product both in terms of visuals and interaction. High fidelity prototypes include all design elements such as colors, typography, images, and real content. They often incorporate interactive features that allow users to navigate through the design as they would in the final product. High fidelity design is used to test usability, gather user feedback, and make final adjustments before moving on to actual development.\n\n**Actual Design:**\nActual design, on the other hand, refers to the finished, implemented product that is ready for use by end users. This is what is produced after the design process (which may include creating high fidelity prototypes) is complete. Actual design involves the final code, fully integrated functionality, and all design elements being in place and operational. It is the end product that users interact with in real-world scenarios.\n\n**Key Differences:**\n1. **Purpose:** High fidelity design is a prototype used in the testing and refinement phase, whereas actual design is the end product ready for users.\n2. **Functionality:** High fidelity designs simulate functionality but may not be fully coded, whereas actual designs have complete, functional code.\n3. **Completion:** High fidelity designs are part of the iterative design process aimed at tweaking and improving, while actual designs represent the final, polished version ready for launch.\n\n**Summary:**\nHigh fidelity designs are detailed, realistic prototypes used to gather feedback and refine the product, whereas actual designs are the final, complete product ready for user interaction and deployment.",
